### Phoenix Wallet API - Idempotency Examples
### These examples show how to use idempotency in lightweight mode

### 1. Create account with idempotency key (first time)
POST http://localhost:3000/v1/accounts
Content-Type: application/json
Idempotency-Key: test-account-creation-001

{}

### 2. Try to create account again with same idempotency key (should return 409 Conflict)
POST http://localhost:3000/v1/accounts
Content-Type: application/json
Idempotency-Key: test-account-creation-001

{}

### 3. Create account with different idempotency key (should work)
POST http://localhost:3000/v1/accounts
Content-Type: application/json
Idempotency-Key: test-account-creation-002

{}

### 4. Transfer tokens with idempotency (replace ADDRESS with actual account address)
POST http://localhost:3000/v1/accounts/ADDRESS/fungible-tokens/FlowToken/withdrawals
Content-Type: application/json
Idempotency-Key: test-transfer-001

{
  "recipient": "0xf8d6e0586b0a20c7",
  "amount": "1.0"
}

### 5. Try same transfer again (should return 409 Conflict)
POST http://localhost:3000/v1/accounts/ADDRESS/fungible-tokens/FlowToken/withdrawals
Content-Type: application/json
Idempotency-Key: test-transfer-001

{
  "recipient": "0xf8d6e0586b0a20c7",
  "amount": "1.0"
}

### 6. Example without idempotency key (should return 400 Bad Request if idempotency is enabled)
POST http://localhost:3000/v1/accounts
Content-Type: application/json

{}